post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_27220074_27220435_0": {"length": 5, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 6181}}, "n3337": {"so_27220074_27220435_0": {"length": 5, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 5942}}, "n4659": {"so_27220074_27220435_0": {"length": 5, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 7683}}}, "27220435": {"Id": "27220435", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>As stated by Matt McNab in comments, the syntax of a braced initialized list is the same regardless of whether you are using it to initialize a scalar or anything else.</p>\n<p>C++11 \u00a75.17 states</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_27220074_27220435_0\">A braced-init-list may appear on the right-hand side of </p>\n<ul>\n<li>an assignment to a scalar, in which case the initializer list shall have at most a single element.</li>\n</ul>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The definition of braced-init-list is (from \u00a78.5):</p>\n<pre>braced-init-list:\n  { initializer-list ,<i>opt</i> }\n  { }</pre>\n<p>where the 'opt' means that the trailing comma is optional.</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "560648", "LastActivityDate": "2014-12-01T01:17:27.447", "Score": "15", "CreationDate": "2014-12-01T01:14:27.250", "ParentId": "27220074", "CommentCount": "6", "LastEditDate": "2014-12-01T01:17:27.447", "OwnerUserId": "1411457"}, "27220074": {"ViewCount": "767", "Body": "<p>I found this weird syntax:</p>\n<pre><code>int a = {1,};\n</code></pre>\n<p>And it works in all the compilers I've tried. How does it compile?</p>\n<p>EDIT: I thought that scalar initializers can only have one element in it, spawning my question. Sorry for all the trouble.</p>\n", "Title": "How does initializing an integer as \"a = {1,}\" compile?", "CreationDate": "2014-12-01T00:30:10.137", "LastActivityDate": "2014-12-01T01:30:09.863", "CommentCount": "3", "FavoriteCount": "0", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditDate": "2014-12-01T01:30:09.863", "LastEditorUserId": "4309946", "Id": "27220074", "Score": "15", "OwnerUserId": "4309946", "Tags": "<c++><c++11><syntax>", "AnswerCount": "1"}});